metadata.name: CELDAS #47
metadata.description:
Cells, called "CELDAS" in Spanish, are spaces separated by lines or stripes in a geometric structure. Generally, cells are formed when the stripes intersect to form a mesh or grid. Each cell formed by these stripes can be filled with a color to create a design.
I love the way I can play with the horizontality and verticality of the stripes to create unique and original geometric patterns, and how through different sizes of stripes an infinity of pieces are formed ranging from the minimalist and sophisticated to the most colorful and expressive, bringing each piece a fresh and current air within a vibrant color palette.
The DNA of this collection is my passion for stripes and colors, both united in a single project that reflects my love in each piece.
I hope you enjoy it as much as I do!

metadata.name: Ceremony #280
metadata.description:
This series celebrates fxhash turning one. #fxhashturnsone

I‚Äôm so grateful for this place and have ho idea how to adequately articulate how much this platform has changed my life, but it has. A million thanks to the team. You are so appreciated as are the artists and collectors that have made this such a beautiful community. ü•Ç

Definitely check out ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode by tapping ‚ÄúF‚Äù or mouse click/tap ‚Äî it will animate (you guessed it) forever and will change its layout every 365 frames, in honor of this wonderful year, and every year after. Some forever modes will ‚Äúnever forget‚Äù and others will fade as they progress. No idea if that‚Äôs a metaphor but it is a trait, that much I know.

All primary sales are donated to Code/Art, which is a charity that uses ‚Äú‚Ä¶Art to Inspire Girls in Computer Science.‚Äù Read about Code/Art here: https://www.code-art.com/

Ceremony uses public domain art (which is the original, more implicit version CC0) made exclusively by women.

See fxtext article linked from the project page for a gallery of the source material and other notes.

Ceremony is also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

F : ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode (tap after initial render completes)
P : Pause/Play
(mouse click/tap also works to start ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode or Pause/Play)

A : Add Grain (only works when paused in ‚ÄúForever‚Äù mode.)
G : Toggle Grain (resets the whole piece)
M : Toggle Matte (resets the whole piece)

S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density (resets the whole piece)
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

If you want to start in "Forever" mode, you can append "&forever=true" to the url in the live view.
You can also add pixel density to the url by appending ‚Äú&density=2‚Äù (or 3, 4, etc) to have it render at higher resolutions by default.

metadata.name: Giants of the Meadow #7
metadata.description:
For my first drop on the new fxhash v1.0 I wanted to make something different. So I challenged myself to write a raymarcher like the ones I use in my shaders but in p5.js and make a fully procedural scene with it. It's a bit tricky to work with vectors once you are used to GLSL, but I managed to write a decent algorithm that scans a grid and slowly draws the image. It draws it with circles and triangles for the grass. The first thing I used for testing was a SDF of a plane with some tall bars on it. Then I was trying different distortions on the shapes and in one moment the results gave me the idea of a scene with mushrooms and grass on an undulated terrain. Later I added a small river and a cloudy sky. I think I was inadvertently inspired by some children's books I had when I was a kid. 

Best viewed full screen.

Features:

Mood: happy - normal - melancholic - strange - sleepy
Mushrooms: 2 - 4 (sometimes one of the mushrooms can only be seen on full screen)
Mushroom height: short - medium - tall
Mushroom fatness: S - M - L - XL
Mushroom shape: 1 - 2 - 3- 4 - 5
Mushroom tilt
Flowers color: white - yellow - pink - cyan - multicolor
River: yes - no
Camera orientation: north - south

metadata.name: eddy currents #31
metadata.description:
When Jackson Pollock met Michael Faraday, a new form of abstract art was created.

eddy currents arise when a conductor is placed in a changing magnetic field. These currents typically form closed loops, and themselves generate a magnetic field which tends to oppose the one that created it.

The metal cores of electrical transformers are often laminated to form thin bounded regions which minimize the eddy currents by constricting them to a small space.

The abstract art embodied in this piece depicts the eddy currents in such laminated structures.

Press "s" to save the image in a .png format file
Press "f" to terminate the drawing early (if you like some intermediate image).
